{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 05:23:09.913150", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Network troubleshooting diagnosis report\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Layer-3 connectivity across the OSPF-based enterprise fabric is healthy. Hosts in user subnets can reach the server farm network 10.200.0.0/24 (DNS, DHCP, load balancer).\\n- Name resolution is correct for all published services.\\n- The Nginx load balancer (web99.local) is reachable and is successfully proxying to its backend pool on a separate, non-routed network (20.200.0.0/24).\\n- One application-level fault detected: web3.local (10.200.0.6) is reachable at IP but has no HTTP service listening; apache2 is inactive. Additionally, at least web0.local presents a non-Apache HTTP server (BaseHTTP Python), which deviates from the stated design (“Apache web servers”).\\n\\nKey observations and evidence\\n1) End-to-end reachability and routing\\n- Broad host-to-host/server pings succeed with 0% loss and RTTs 1–6 ms (functions.get_reachability).\\n- Example host net config:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.19/24 via 10.1.1.1 (DHCP); host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.19/24 via 10.2.1.1 (DHCP) (functions.get_host_net_config).\\n- From hosts:\\n  - DNS server (10.200.0.2) reachable: 0% loss, ~2–3 ms (functions.ping_pair).\\n  - Load balancer (10.200.0.7) reachable: 0% loss, ~2–5 ms (functions.ping_pair).\\n\\n2) DNS correctness\\n- getent hosts on hosts returns:\\n  - web99.local → 10.200.0.7\\n  - web0.local → 10.200.0.3, web1.local → 10.200.0.4, web2.local → 10.200.0.5, web3.local → 10.200.0.6\\n- Zone file on dns_server confirms these mappings (functions.exec_shell on dns_server, zone dump).\\n\\n3) Load balancer health and backend isolation\\n- web99.local HTTP: consistent 200 OK; TTFB ~0.2–0.4 s, total ~1.0–1.2 s from multiple hosts (functions.curl_web_test).\\n- Load balancer Nginx config (functions.cat_file on load_balancer):\\n  - upstream web99 uses servers 20.200.0.2:80, 20.200.0.3:80, 20.200.0.4:80.\\n  - LB NICs: eth0 10.200.0.7/24, eth1 20.200.0.1/24; default via 10.200.0.1 (functions.get_host_net_config).\\n- LB to backends: ICMP OK (<1 ms) and HTTP 200 OK on all three 20.200.0.{2,3,4} (functions.exec_shell).\\n- From user hosts, 20.200.0.0/24 is not reachable (ICMP “Destination Net Unreachable” via gateway), and HTTP attempts time out—this matches the design that backend servers are not directly accessible from hosts (functions.ping_pair, curl tests to 20.200.0.x).\\n\\n4) Front-end web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6)\\n- web0.local and web1.local and web2.local return HTTP 200 from hosts.\\n  - Notably, web0.local shows header “Server: BaseHTTP/0.6 Python/3.11.2” (not Apache), which deviates from the stated “Apache web servers” design (host_1_1_1_1 curl header).\\n- web3.local (10.200.0.6):\\n  - ICMP reachable from hosts (~2.5 ms) (functions.ping_pair).\\n  - HTTP fails (curl code 000 from hosts).\\n  - On web_server_3: no process listening on port 80 (functions.netstat), apache2 service is inactive (dead) (functions.systemctl_ops).\\n\\nAssessment of anomalies\\n- Service outage: web3.local (10.200.0.6)\\n  - Symptom: TCP/80 not listening; clients get HTTP failures while ICMP works.\\n  - Localization: web_server_3 host.\\n  - Root cause: apache2 inactive (dead), confirmed by systemd status and absence of a listening socket.\\n\\n- Service inconsistency: web0.local (10.200.0.3)\\n  - Symptom: HTTP header reports “BaseHTTP/0.6 Python/3.11.2” rather than Apache.\\n  - Localization: web_server_0 host.\\n  - Likely cause: non-Apache HTTP server running instead of Apache (design deviation). Web service is up, so impact is functional but not per design.\\n\\n- Backend isolation validation (not a fault):\\n  - Hosts cannot reach 20.200.0.0/24; gateways return Destination Net Unreachable; curl to those IPs fails from hosts.\\n  - This matches the intended security/segmentation: load balancer-only access to backends.\\n  - Load balancer has full connectivity to the backend network and successfully proxies to it.\\n\\nOverall network health\\n- OSPF routing across the fabric appears normal; no path loss observed to the 10.200.0.0/24 server farm from user subnets.\\n- DHCP lease and default routing on hosts are present and valid.\\n- DNS resolution is correct for the local zone and supports end-to-end access to services.\\n- Load-balancing path is healthy; user-facing service web99.local is performing normally.\\n\\nConclusions\\n- The network fabric and routing control plane are healthy; reachability to server farm and the load-balancer is normal.\\n- The backend server network (20.200.0.0/24) is correctly isolated from hosts and accessible to the load balancer only.\\n- Two application-layer issues are identified in the server farm:\\n  1) web_server_3 (10.200.0.6) has its HTTP service down (apache2 inactive), causing web3.local to fail over HTTP.\\n  2) web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) is serving via a Python BaseHTTP server rather than Apache, deviating from the intended design, though the service responds with 200 OK.\\n\\nNo mitigation actions are proposed here per the request; findings focus on anomaly detection, localization, and root causes., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='754a3082-c1b9-4d4c-97bf-3e0d69301cc5'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
